const char *__cdecl Reflection::Internal::GetFuncName<class Attribute::Detail::StringAttrBase<class Attribute::ObjectGroup>>(void)
Server Authoritative
The server performs the evaluation of the node's logic and networks the results to the client.  The client does not perform any logic and just follows the results of the server
Client Simulate
The client performs the evaluation of the node's logic itself.  No network synchronization is performed.  In order to work, all children of a ClientSimulate node are forced to also be ClientSimulate, regardless of what their actual setting is.

materials/editor/prefab_icon.vmat
Map File
fixupEntityNames
useTargetNameAsPrefix
loadIfNested
visexclude
displayColor
prefabRuntimeEntity
loadAtRuntime
Specifies the map file whose contents will be referenced by this prefab.
Target Name
Specifies the name by which the prefab can be referenced by entity i/o. The set of inputs the prefab has is defined by the map relays in the target map.
Fixup entity names
If enabled, any entity target names within the prefab will have a prefix applied to ensure they are unique. This prevents any issues with entities in two different prefabs having name collisions.
Prefix with Target Name
fixupEntityNames == false || targetName == ""
If this is enabled and name fixup is enabled, the prefix used for name fixup will be the prefab target name instead of the unique id. If the target name is empty then the prefab the unique id will still be used as the prefix. Note that if two prefabs use the same target name for their prefix it will be possible to have entities inside the prefabs end up with name collisions.
Load if nested
If enabled the prefab will be loaded when it is the child of another prefab, if disabled, this prefab will not be loaded if it is the child of another prefab.
Not a Vis Contributor
If set, the contents of the prefab will not be included in visibility calculations.
Display Color
A color which will be used to identify the prefab within Hammer, does not have any affect on the compiled map
Create Prefab Runtime Entity
If enabled, there will be a point_prefab entity at runtime representing this prefab as an EntityIO target (requires Relays and a Target Name). Map Relay connections will not be baked, but will instead route through this entity.
Load at runtime
If enabled the prefab will not be baked into the parent map during map compile, but instead will be dynamically loaded in the game. This requires the target map to be compiled separately. Additionally this requires support for dynamic loading of maps by the game, which may not be supported by all games and game systems. Do not use without checking to see if this is fully supported by the game you are working on.

renderWithDynamic
Smart Prop File
Specifies the smart prop which this object will instantiate
Whole object tint color
A tint color to apply to the entire smart prop. The evaluation of the smart prop receives this color and may use it directly or may modify it before assigning a tint to the individual parts of the smart prop.
Lock Evaluation
Disable updates from the specified smart prop file.
Constrain To Prefab
If enabled and the smart prop is inside a prefab, the evaluation of the smart prop considers only the contents of the parent prefab, not anything outside the prefab. For example, if enabled, any traces performed by the smart prop will only hit other objects within the parent prefab.
evaluationLocked == true
Input Shapes
Alpha of the fade, where 0 = fully transparent and 255 = fully opaque.
Render Properties
Cull Distance
Maximum distance at which individual parts of the prop will be visible. If 0 the setting on individual parts of the smart prop will be used.
Fade Start Distance
Distance at which each part of the prop starts to fade. Only applies if Cull Distance > 0. Positive values are absolute values, while negative values are relative to the cull distance. For example Cull Distance = 100, Start Fade Distance = -30 means the object will start fading at 70 units away and will disappear when 100 units away.
Select a an entity to specify a location to sample lighting from, instead of using this entity's bounding box center.
Lighting
what type of shadows should be cast from this object.
Enabled
Baked Lighting Mode
Should baked lighting be generated for this object. If default is selected, the choice is left to individual parts.
Lightprobed
Lightmapped
Lightmap Scale Bias
Increase or decrease the resolution of the lightmap applied to this object.
Scale down by 8
Scale down by 4
Scale down by 2
Default (no scale)
Scale up by 2
Scale up by 4
Scale up by 8
Bake Lighting As If Double-Sided
Bake lighting as if this were double-sided geometry. Useful on geometry with pre-culled backfaces whose neighbors have lighting errors caused by saw-too-many-backfaces sample invalidation.
Collisions
Specifies how collision shapes are to generated.
Build Settings
Not Solid
Use axis-aligned box
Use oriented Box
Use VPhysics
Vis Occluder
If true this geometry is used as an occluder for precomputed visibility
Render To Cubemaps
If true, this geometry renders into baked cube maps
Disable in low quality mode
Do not render when using the lowest quality video settings. This object is a non-essential detail.
Bake To World
If true this geometry will be baked into the world geometry of the map so that the model is not referenced at runtime.
Disable Merging
If true this will not be merged with other geometry during map compile (reduces rendering efficiency).
Render with Dynamic Objects
Render this object with other dynamic objects

game:tools/images/hammer/tool_lattice_activated.png
CMapDeformerSimple
Y-Axis
Z-Axis
Simple Deformer
bendAxis
bendAngle
bendPoint
bendRadius
Deformation Axis
Specifies the local space axis which the deformer will bend around.
Bend Angle
Specifies the angle of bend to apply in degrees. Range is [ -360, 360 ]. Negative values cause the bend to occur in the opposite direction.
Bend Point
0 to 1 value specifying the location on the local x-axis of the deformer around which the bend will occur. A value of 0 means the bend will occur around the minimum end of the deformer, a value of 1 means the bend will occur around the maximum end of the deformer, a value of 0.5 means the bend will occur at the center of the deformer volume.
Bend Radius
Specifies the radius of the bend. When the value is 0, the radius is automatically calculated to preserve the length of the deformer volume for the specified angle. If an explict radius is specified then the inside edge of the bend will match this radius for all angle values, however this will result the the deformer changing the length of its contents.

Displacement
Layer containing the height or displacement values defining the surface on which the objects will be placed.
Density
Layer which defines the density of object placement over the terrain.
Tint
Layer which provides a tint color to be applied to objects
Object Spacing
Controls the average distance between any two object locations. However with random offsets object locations may be closer.
Randomness
0 to 1 value controlling how much random offset is applied to each point. A value of 0 will generate a regular grid of points.
Random Seed
A seed value used when generating the point positions. Changing the value will change the random distribution

Specify the type of culling of the skeleton for animated models.\t\t\t<br><b>NOTE</b>: Models without animations are always Aggressive.<br>\n\t\t\t<table>\t\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<th align="left"><b>Aggressive</b></th>\t\t\t<th align="left">Removes any bones which are not skinned or referenced</th>\t\t\t</tr>\t\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<th align="left"><b>Leaf Only</b></th>\t\t\t<th align="left">Removes any bones which are not skinned or referenced that have no children</th>\t\t\t</tr>\t\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<th align="left"><b>None</b></th>\t\t\t<th align="left">Doesn't remove any bones</th>\t\t\t</tr>\t\t\t</table>

Generates a turn layer from a 3 frame animation\n<ul>\n<li>Frame 0 :: Left Pose</li>\n<li>Frame 1 :: Center Pose</li>\n<li>Frame 2 :: Right Pose</li>\n</ul>\nIt will generate:\n<ul>\n<li>3 implicit animations\n<ul>\n<li>@<strong>&lt;NAME&gt;</strong>_lookFrame_0 :: ( Frame 0 ) - ( Frame 1 )</li>\n<li>@<strong>&lt;NAME&gt;</strong>_lookFrame_1 :: ( Frame 1 ) - ( Frame 1 ) - Note that this is an empty animation</li>\n<li>@<strong>&lt;NAME&gt;</strong>_lookFrame_2 :: ( Frame 2 ) - ( Frame 1 )</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>A pose parameter named "turn" by default with the range [-1, 1]</li>\n<li>A 1D Blend additive sequence with pose parameter values [-1, 0, 1]\n<ul>\n<li>[ @_lookFrame_0, @_lookFrame_1, @_lookFrame_2 ]</li>\n<li>The 1D Blend sequence should be applied to runs with an AddLayer <img src='game:tools/images/modeldoc_editor/outliner_icon_addlayer.png' /> node</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>

import_bone_scales
Import Bone Scales
Whether or not to import bone scales.  False by default (i.e. override bone scales to 1.0) for legacy compatibility.  Only applicable to fbx files.
start_frame
Start Frame
The frame at which to start using animation data.  By default it's 0, the first frame of the animation.
end_frame
The frame at which to end using animation data.  By default it's the last frame of the animation.
Frame Rate
Specify the framerate at which to play back the animation.  It is filled in from the data in the animation file so normally it doesn't need to be modified.
reverse
Reverse
Reverse the direction of the animation.  This happens after the frame range is truncated.
Import Bone Scales only applies to FBX and DMX input files, will be ignored for %s files

RemoveBoneKeepChildren
tools/images/modeldoc_editor/outliner_icon_removebonekeepchildren.png
Removes the named bone but keeps all children and descendent bones. When the specified bone has skin weights, the weights will be transferred to the bone's parent.  In the case of skin weights and no parent bone, the skin weights will be distributed amongst the bone's children. If there are skin weights and no parent or child bones, then the mesh will have no bones and no skinning.

AnimBase
Base class for animations which are nodes that map to a compiled animation
AnimBaseParams
activity_name
Activity Name
Primary activity for this animation.  To add an activity modifier, add an ActivityModifier child node.<p><span style="color:#ffff00"><b>NOTE</b></span>: Animgraph animations should not use activities or activity weights.
activity_weight
Activity Weight
Weight list to apply to this animation.<p><span style="color:#ffff00"><b>NOTE</b></span>: Animgraph animations should not use activities or activity weights.
Weight list to apply to this animation at runtime.<p><span style="color:#ffff00"><b>NOTE</b></span>: Animgraph animations should not apply a weightlist here.  When using animgraph, a weightlist should be applied via a <span style="color:#7b364f"><b>Bone Mask</b></span> node in the graph.
fade_in_time
Fade In Time
Time in seconds from the start of the animation over which it will fade int when it starts playing.
fade_out_time
Fade Out Time
Time in seconds from the end of the animation over which it will fade out when it stops playing.
looping
Looping
Specify whether the animation loops.
delta
Delta
Specifies the animation's inherent blend mode.<p>If <b>TRUE</b> the animation will <b>ADD</b> itself onto the current animation stack.<p>If <b>FALSE</b> the animation will <b>BLEND</b> itself onto the current animation stack.<p><span style="color:#ffff00"><b>NOTE</b></span>: Animgraph animations should normally leave this at the default value of <b>FALSE</b>. The blend mode is set on the Animgraph node explicitly.
worldSpace
WorldSpace
Specifies the animation's inherent blend mode to worldspace, mutally exclusive with delta.<p>If <b>TRUE</b> the animation will <b>WORLDSPACE</b> blend itself onto the current animation stack.<p>If <b>FALSE</b> the animation will <b>BLEND</b> itself onto the current animation stack.<p><span style="color:#ffff00"><b>NOTE</b></span>: Animgraph animations should normally leave this at the default value of <b>FALSE</b>. The blend mode is set on the Animgraph node explicitly.
Hidden
Specify whether the animation should be hidden from the compiled view outliner on the right and pulldowns.
anim_markup_ordered
Anim Markup Ordered
Specify that the animation markup child nodes for this animation should be processed in the order they appear.
disable_compression
Disable Compression
Turn off animation compression for this animation.<p><span style="color:#aa0000"><b>NOTE</b></span>: This significantly increases the size of the animation data.<p>Normally it should be false but if there are obvious compression artifacts, typically in tiny rotations, disabling compression may fix those.
animgraph_additive
AnimGraph Additive
If animation has been subtracted in ModelDoc to create an additive animation to be used with AnimGraph, set this to true
Delta & WorldSpace are mutually exclusive, only check one of them
"%s" attribute should not be used when using AnimGraph, reset value to default if possible.
Keyframe animation data

AnimSmoothLoop
Finds the difference between the last frame and the first frame in the animation and blends that difference across the boundary.The specified range is from some negative value( number of frames back from the last frame ) to 0, and from 0 to some positive number of frames after the first frame.  This is useful when building a looping animation out of a portion of a non - looping animation, or even cleaning up a animation that is supposed to loop but has a slight hitch.
tools/images/modeldoc_editor/outliner_icon_animsmoothloop.png

frames_from_end

Discards animation channels by type and name.\n<br>The channel will end up with the bind pose value as defined by the model.\n<br>Name can be a wildcard glob, i.e. use * to discard all channels of the specified type.\n<br>If Static Only is checked the animation channel must also be static, i.e. Channel's value doesn't change during the animation.\n<br><b>NOTE</b>: Can only discard an entire bone channel, not just the translation, rotation or scale components.\n<br><b>NOTE</b>: As this is an animation modifier, it can be applied at the folder level to all animation nodes contained in it.\n

AclParameters
tools/images/modeldoc_editor/outliner_icon_acl.png
Parameters which control the ACL compression for animation.
compression_level
Compression Level
Applies to skeletal animation only.<br><br>Specify how aggressively to attempt to reduce the memory footprint. Higher levels will try more permutations and bit rates. The higher the level, the slower the compression but the smaller the memory footprint. <br><b>NOTE</b>: Currently lowest, low and medium are all equivalent.
virtual_vertex_distance
Virtual Vertex Distance
Applies to skeletal animation only.<br><br>https://github.com/nfrechette/acl/blob/develop/docs/creating_a_skeleton.md<br><br>The virtual vertex distance is used by the error metric function. It will measure the error of a vertex at that particular distance from the bone in object space. This distance should be large enough to contain the vast majority of the visible vertices skinned on that particular bone. The algorithm ensures that all vertices contained up to this distance will have an error lower than the supplied error threshold in the CompressionSettings. It is generally sufficient for this value to be approximate and it is often safe to use the same value for every bone in humanoid characters. A value of 3cm (or ~1 inch in game units) is good enough for cinematographic quality for most characters. While visible vertices around the torso will often be further away than this, finger tips and facial bones will be closer than that. Because the compressed track data is stored in relative space of the parent bone, any error will accumulate down the hierarchy. This means that in order to keep the leaf bones within that accuracy threshold, all the parent bones in that chain will require even higher accuracy.
translation_constant_threshold
Translation Constant Threshold
Threshold value to use when detecting if translation tracks are constant or default. In game units, i.e. inches
error_threshold
Error Threshold
Applies to skeletal animation only.<br><br>See :: https://github.com/nfrechette/acl/blob/develop/docs/compressing_a_raw_clip.md<br><br>The last important setting to choose is the error_threshold. This is used in conjunction with the error metric and the virtual vertex distance from the skeleton in order to guarantee that a certain quality is maintained. A default value of 0.01cm (or ~0.004 inches in game units) is safe to use and it most likely should never be changed unless the units you are using differ. If you do run into issues where compression artifacts are visible, in all likelihood the virtual vertex distance used on the problematic bones is not conservative enough.
tracks_precision
Tracks Precision
Applies to morph animation only.<br><br>This is the per component precision threshold to try and attain when optimizing the bit rate. If the error is below the precision threshold, we will remove bits until we reach it without exceeding it. If the error is above the precision threshold, we will add more bits until we lower it underneath. 
tracks_constant_threshold
Tracks Constant Threshold
ActivityModifier
tools/images/modeldoc_editor/outliner_icon_activitymodifier.png
An extra string and weight to apply to the primary activity assigned to an animation
Number

AnimForceBoneScale
Override bone scale information on an animation

AnimForceBoneScaleLerp
Overrides the bone scale of the specified bone over the specified frame range specified by the 2D animation curve.<br>The Frame is the X Axis (horizontal).<br>The Scale is Y Axis (vertical).<br>Any frames which fall outside of the frame range are left alone.<br>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Ctrl + Mouse Move</td>\n    <td>Snap Frames</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Alt + Mouse Move</td>\n    <td>Snap Values</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Wheel</td>\n    <td>Zoom</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Ctrl + Wheel</td>\n    <td>Zoom X</td>\n  </tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</center><br><center><br><img src='game:tools/images/modeldoc_editor/docs_anim_markup_curve.png'/><br></center>Force Bone Scale nodes are processed in the order they appear under the AnimFile node and will overwrite previously written data if the frame ranges overlap.<b>NOTE</b>: Although the Input/Frame Range are floats, integers should be used. Curve data is not evaluated at run time. The curve is sampled once per frame of the animation and the values are linearly interpolated between frames.<br>
The name of the bone which will have the scale valve overwritten.
AnimForceBoneScaleSet
Applies a bone scale set to the animation over the specified frame range specified by the 2D animation curve.<br>The Input Range is the X Axis range (horizontal) and corresponds to the frame range.<br>The Output Range is the Y Axis range (vertical) and is the scale set weight value over the frame range.<br>Any frames which fall outside of the frame range are left alone.<br><center><br><img src='game:tools/images/modeldoc_editor/docs_anim_markup_curve.png'/><br></center>AnimForceBoneScaleSet nodes are processed in the order they appear under the AnimFile node and will overwrite previously written data if the frame ranges overlap.<b>NOTE</b>: Although the Input/Frame Range are floats, integers should be used. Curve data is not evaluated at run time. The curve is sampled once per frame of the animation and the values are linearly interpolated between frames.<br>

Applies an animation markup over a specified frame range with a value controlled by an editable 2D animation curve.<br>The Input Range is the X Axis range (horizontal) and corresponds to the frame range.<br>The Output Range is the Y Axis range (vertical) and is the value over the frame range.<br>Any frames which fall outside of the frame range are left alone.<br><center>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Ctrl + Mouse Move</td>\n    <td>Snap Frames</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Alt + Mouse Move</td>\n    <td>Snap Values</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Wheel</td>\n    <td>Zoom</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Ctrl + Wheel</td>\n    <td>Zoom X</td>\n  </tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</center><br><center><br><img src='game:tools/images/modeldoc_editor/docs_anim_markup_curve.png'/><br></center><b>NOTE</b>: Although the Input/Frame Range are floats, integers should be used. Curve data is not evaluated at run time. The curve is sampled once per frame of the animation and the values are linearly interpolated between frames.<br>
CurveEditor( { extended=true input_name="Frame" output_name="Value" } ) 
An editable curve to control a value over a specified frame range which will be used to apply markup to an animation.
Specify the initial frame range:

Name of the target smart prop resource (.vsmart) to evaluate.
If enabled, any changes made to the evaluation state by the target smart prop (as well as modifiers) will only apply locally and will not affect the evaluation state of the parent. Disabling this will allow modifications to the evaluation state by the referenced smart prop to apply the current state of the of the parent. For example if the referenced smart prop applies a transform and you want the transform to affect the elements in the parent after this element, then you should disable local evaluation state.

+Origin
Specifies the origin point for the start of the trace. To trace from the current position, set to < 0, 0, 0 > and set the coordinate space to Element Space
Coordinate space the origin is specified in. Using Element space allows specifying a value relative to the current position. However, world space should generally be used when for variable values.
Offset to apply to the specified origin along the trace direction to compute the starting point of the trace.
+Result
How much should the surface normal up direction influence the final orientation. [ 0, 1 ] where 0 = don't modify the orientation, 1 = completely re-orient to match the surface.
If No Surface Hit
Specifies the behavior when the trace does not hit a surface.
Trace filtering
Do not trace against tool materials (attribute 'tools.toolsmaterial').
Do not trace against sky materials (attribute 'mapbuilder.sky').
Do not trace against no draw materials (material attribute 'mapbuilder.nodraw').
Do not trace against translucent materials (materials with 'alphatest' or 'translucent' attributes).
Do not trace against any models (only hit world geometry).
Do not trace against dynamic entities which may move in game.

ScaleMode_t

CSmartPropVariable_ScaleMode
PickMode_t
CSmartPropAttributePickMode
CSmartPropVariable_PickMode

CSmartPropSelectionCriteria_EndCap
CSmartPropElement_FitOnLine
MVDataComponentValidGrandParents
No scaling
Do not allow selected elements to be scaled, the parts may not fit the line exactly
Scale last
Apply scale to the last element in order to fit the line. Only proceed to scale additional elements if the scale range of the last element is not sufficient.
Scale equally
Attempt to apply the same amount of scale to all of the elements placed on the line while still respecting their size constraints.
Maximize scale
Each element will be scaled to is maximum allowable size that will still fit on the line.
SCALE_END_TO_FIT
SCALE_EQUALLY
SCALE_MAXIMIZE
Largest fitting
Pick the largest child element that will fit in the remaining length of the line, repeat this process until the line is full or no child will fit in the remaining length.
Random fitting
Pick a random choice from the child elements that will fit within the remaining length, repeat this process until the line is full or no child will fit in the remaining length.
Place all in order
Place all of the child elements in the order they are specified even if they do not fit the line or do not fill the line. NOTE: end cap settings are ignored in this mode.
LARGEST_FIRST
ALL_IN_ORDER

Specifies the length of the line that will be taken up if this element is selected.
Can this object be scaled. If enabled the minimum and maximum lengths must be set to specify the size range of allowable scale.
Minimum length
m_bAllowScale == false
Minimum allowable length for the object. Must be <= length. If length is 100 and minimum length is 20, then the object may be assigned a scale in the rage [ 0.2, 1.0 ].
Maximum length
Maximum allowable length for the object. Must be >= length. If length is 100 and maximum length is 160, then the object may be assigned a scale in the rage [ 1.0, 1.6 ].

CSmartPropElement_PickOne
Specifies the method to use to determine which positions this element should be placed at along the path.
( m_PlaceAtPositions == ALL ) || ( m_PlaceAtPositions == START_AND_END ) || ( m_PlaceAtPositions == CONTROL_POINTS )
Specifies the spacing between positions. For example, a value of 1 will place the element at very position, 2 every other position, 3 every third position
Specifies an offset to use when determining the Nth position to place an element at. For example if placing at every third position with an offset of 0, an element will appear at positions 1, 4, 7, and so on. But if an offset of 2 is set instead of 0, then an element will appear at positions 3, 6, and 9 and so on.
Should this element be placed at the first positions on the path
Should this element be placed at the last positions on the path
Valid Path Positions
Specifies the path positions at which this element may appear.
m_PlaceAtPositions
m_nPlaceEveryNthPosition
m_nNthPositionIndexOffset
m_bAllowAtStart
m_bAllowAtEnd
Name of the path to use. This path name will show up in the property editor when selecting a placement of this smart prop in Hammer, allowing selection of a path object in the map to use.
Spacing between points on the path
Offset from the start of the path to place the first point.
Offset from path
Offset to apply to the path, specifies a horizontal and vertical offset to apply relative to the up direction.
Path Evaluation Space
Specifies the space in which the provided input path is to be evalauted.<br><br><b>World Space</b>: The input path will be evaluated in world space, such that child elements will be placed directly on the target path regardless of the transform of the smart prop object. <br><b>Object Space</b>: The world space transform of the input path will be ignored and instead the path will be evaluated relative to the transform of the smart prop object. <br><b>Element Space</b>: The world space transform of the input path will be ignored and instead the path will be evaluated relative to the transform of the current element within the smart prop. 
If true, treat the specified up direction as fixed up direction to apply to all elements placed on the path. If false the up direction is just an initial direction.
Compute the spacing distance in the 2d plane defined by the up direction. Most useful when using a fixed up direction, if maintaining a distance in the 2d plane is more important than maintaing distance along the path.
If not using a fixed up direction, provides an initial up direction which will be used to determine the orientation of first element on the path, after that the elements will incrementally update to follow the path and may not match this direction. If Use Fixed Up direction is specified, then all elements will use this direction to deterime their up direction.
A set of points defining a path to use when an external path isn't specified. This will be used in the preview and thumbnail for the smart prop. It will also be used when the smart prop is placed in Hammer before a path is selected.
Place on Path
An element which places an instance of its child elements at a specified interval along a path.
m_PathName
m_flOffsetAlongPath
m_vPathOffset
m_PathSpace
m_bUseFixedUpDirection
m_bUseProjectedDistance
m_DefaultPath
SmartPropPathPositions_t
CSmartPropAttributePathPositions
CSmartPropVariable_PathPositions
CSmartPropSelectionCriteria_PathPosition
CSmartPropElement_PlaceOnPath
All positions
Place at all positions along the path
Every N positions
Place at every Nth position along the path, skipping over the other positions
Only at start and end
Only place at the start or end of the path
Path control points
Place at path control points instead of every point along the path, when this is selected the path spacing no longer applies
START_AND_END
CONTROL_POINTS
SmartPropAttributeEditor(enum:SmartPropPathPositions_t)
Path Positions
Specifies the set of positions that are valid for path placement.
Deformation Enabled
Should the deformation be applied. If disabled the children will still be placed, but will not be deformed. Esentially making the element behave as a group.
A local offset to apply to the base volume of the deformer that will not apply to its children.
A local rotation to apply to apply the base volume of the deformer that will not apply to its children. This can be used to alter the direction of the deformation.
Size of the base volume to be deformed.
Bend amount to apply, specified in degrees. Bend occurs along the local x-axis and bends around the local z-axis
[ 0, 1 ] Value specifying the location along the local x-axis the bend will occur around
Radius of the bend. If 0 the radius will be computed automatically to preserve the length of the inner edge of the x-axis. If a non-zero value is specified then the inner edge will maintain this radius, but its length will change.
Bend Deformer
Creates a bend deformer that is applied to child elements. The deformation bends the local space x-axis around the local space z-axis. The Angles property can be used to rotate the local axis to change the direction of deformation.
m_bDeformationEnabled
m_vOrigin
m_vAngles
m_flBendAngle
m_flBendPoint
m_flBendRadius
CSmartPropElement_BendDeformer
CSmartPropElement_PlaceInSphere
Specifies how the positions are computed based on the radius.
Specifies the method to be used to distribute.
m_DistributionMode == RANDOM
0 to 1 value indicating the amout of random offset that should be applied to the reguluarly spaced positions

Quick scan or full scan:
<h4>We can quickly use the asset system to find most asset references (about 98%%). Assets that will not be found include map references when the map has not been recompiled, disabled references in maps or models, and assets used to preview in modeldoc and the particle system editor. A full scan to find all references can be done, but will take ten minutes or longer the first time.  After that the results will be saved and subsequent scans will be much quicker.  <br> Do you wish to use the quicker method (yes), or the full scan method (no)?</h4>

Filter:
props _color .psd
Match any number of substrings (AND), separate with spaces:
_color .psd
Match all substrings (AND), separate with spaces:
-.vmdl
Match anything without a substring, add a - prefix:
::menu-indicator{width:0px;}
Match a substring:
_color .psd | _color .tga | _ao -.vtex -.txt
Combine everything:
.psd | .png | .jpg | .tga | .tif | .tiff
Match any of multiple substrings (OR):
.psd | .png
Match one substring or another (OR), use | to separate:
props color -.vtex
Combine with excluded substrings:
/props/ .fbx
Only - and | are special characters:
rect
boneflags
cloth
collision
attach
vdata
vsnap
